{{multiple issues| {{context|date=December 2012}} {{lead too short|date=December 2012}} }} {{Infobox website | name = Citizinvestor | logo = | logo_size = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = <!-- or: | logocaption = --> | screenshot = | collapsible = <!-- set as "on", "y", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank --> | collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default "Screenshot"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set --> | background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) --> | screenshot_size = | screenshot_alt = | caption = | url = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | slogan = | commercial = <!-- "Yes", "No" or leave blank --> | type = Civic crowdfunding | registration = | language = | num_users = | content_license = <!-- or: | content_licence = --> | programming_language = | owner = Jordan Raynor, Tony DeSisto, Erik Rapprich, and Joy Randels | author = <!-- or: creator / authors / creators --> | editor = <!-- or: | editors = --> | launch_date = <!-- {{start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | revenue = | alexa = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady}} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) --> | ip = | issn = <!-- ISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | oclc = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | current_status = | footnotes = }}
'''Citizinvestor''' is an American-based [[civic crowdfunding]] website that describes itself as a "crowdfunding and [[civic engagement]] platform for local government projects."
==Overview==
Citizinvestor is an online [[crowdfunding]] platform specifically focused on raising money for public projects and community [[infrastructure]], started in [[Tampa, Florida]] by Jordan Raynor, Tony DeSisto, Erik Rapprich, and Joy Randels.<ref name=Tampa>{{cite news|last=Morelli|first=Keith|title=Kayak commute dream is a citizen-investor idea|url=http://tbo.com/news/kayak-commute-dream-is-a-citizen-investor-idea-510157|accessdate=28 February 2014|newspaper=Tampa Tribune|date=23 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://techpresident.com/news/22626/kickstarter-inspiring-civically-minded-crowdfunding-sites|title=Three Kickstarter-Inspired, Civically Minded Crowdfunding Sites|last=Neubauer|first=Miranda|date=31 July 2012|website=TechPresident|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://archive.is/20130414193053/http://www.crowdsourcing.org/editorial/citizinvestor-launches-in-philadelphia/19234/3|title=Citizinvestor Launches in Philadelphia|date=2013-04-14|work=archive.is|access-date=2018-07-31}}</ref> It was launched in partnership with the city of [[Philadelphia]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mashable.com/2012/10/10/city-crowdfunding/#9qcVtK84DGqf|title=Crowdfunding Startups Let You Be Your City's Urban Planner|last=Drell|first=Lauren|work=Mashable|access-date=2018-07-31|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.phillymag.com/the_philly_post/2012/09/14/philadelphia-citizinvestor-citizens/|title=With “Citizinvestors,” Philly Will Try to Crowdfund its Way to a Better Future – Philadelphia Magazine|last=Mathis|first=Joel|date=2012-09-14|work=Philadelphia Magazine|access-date=2018-07-31|language=en-US}}</ref>
It was inspired by a case in [[Davis Islands (Tampa)|Davis Islands]] where the community wanted a swimming pool repaired, but the city did not have the finances to do so;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1680600/citizinvestor-crowdfunding-for-community-projects|title=Citizinvestor: Crowdfunding For Community Projects|last=Schiller|first=Ben|date=2012-10-01|work=Fast Company|access-date=2018-07-31|language=en-US}}</ref> citizens successfully raised the funds with events and going door-to-door and this became the model for Citizinvestor.<ref name="Tampa" /> The founders hope to "spark a rise of [[Micro-philanthropy|micro philanthropists]]".<ref name="Tampa" /> The platform allows citizens to promote independent projects through a [[petition]] process and also works with city officials to crowdfund civic projects that were planned but abandoned due to budget constraints.<ref name="Tampa" />
While anyone can start petitions for new projects, projects can only be submitted by government entities, usually [[Local government|municipal governments]].<ref name=":0" /> Donations are [[tax deductible]],<ref name=":1" /> and donors are not charged if their project does not reach its funding target.<ref name=":0" /> Unlike other crowdfunding platforms, no perks/rewards are offered.<ref name=":0" /> The site's initial focus was on projects: between $10,000 and $20,000.<ref name=":0" />
Citizinvestor also offers a [[software as a service]] product, Citizinvestor Connect. Local [[municipalities]], [[public-private partnerships]], [[Economic development organization|economic development organizations]], and [[nonprofits]] can license the platform and customize it for their organization, leveraging it to raise funds and engage with their community.
