{{refimprove|date=January 2014}} {{chembox | Verifiedfields = changed | verifiedrevid = 428800398 | ImageFile = Ethyl cellulose.png | IUPACName = | OtherNames = Cellulose, ethyl ether; ethylated cellulose; ethylcellulose; E462 |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|CAS}} | CASNo = 9004-57-3 | UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|changed|FDA}} | UNII = 7Z8S9VYZ4B | PubChem = | ChemSpiderID_Ref = {{chemspidercite|changed|chemspider}} | ChemSpiderID = none | SMILES = }} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | Formula = variable | MolarMass = variable | Appearance = | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} |Section3={{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Ethyl cellulose''' is a derivative of [[cellulose]] in which some of the [[hydroxyl group]]s on the repeating [[glucose]] units are converted into [[ethyl group|ethyl]] [[ether]] groups. The number of ethyl groups can vary depending on the manufacturer.
It is mainly used as a thin-film coating material for coating paper, vitamin and medical pills, and for thickeners in cosmetics and in industrial processes.
Food grade ethyl cellulose is one of few non-toxic films and thickeners which are not water soluble. This property allows it to be used to safeguard ingredients from water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dow.com/dowwolff/en/industrial_solutions/polymers/ethylcellulose/|title=Ethylcellulose|website=www.dow.com}}</ref>
Ethyl cellulose is also used as a food additive as an [[emulsifier]] (E462).
